"""
mkt-christ | Exodus | chapters 39-40 | 81 verses (all missing)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-exodus-39-40-fill.py

Key Christological types:
- 39:32,43: 'The work was completed' / Moses blessed them -> John 19:30; Gen 2:1-2; Matt 3:17
- 39:42: 'Done exactly as commanded' -> Christ's perfect obedience (John 8:29; Heb 5:8-9)
- 40:20: Tablets in ark, mercy seat on top -> law covered by mercy; Rom 3:25
- 40:21: Veil screens the ark -> the veil torn at the cross (Matt 27:51); Heb 10:19-20
- 40:26-27: Golden incense altar -> Christ's perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25; Rev 8:3-4)
- 40:33: Moses 'completed the work' -> 'It is finished' (John 19:30); Gen 2:2 echo
- 40:34-35: Glory fills the tabernacle / Moses cannot enter -> John 1:14; Heb 10:19 (bold access through Christ)
- 40:38: Cloud by day, fire by night (final verse) -> the Emmanuel goal; Rev 21:3 consummation
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS = {
  "39": {
    "1": "<p>From the blue, purple, and scarlet material they made the vestments for sanctuary service and the sacred garments for Aaron — all exactly as YHWH commanded. Exodus 39 is the execution chapter corresponding to the instruction chapters (28-29): every garment described in chapter 28 is now made in chapter 39. The correspondence is deliberate and precise. The NT parallel is Jesus's declaration in John 17:4: 'I have completed the work you gave me to do' — the execution matches the command with perfect fidelity. The faithfulness of the craftsmen to the heavenly pattern is the OT form of Christ's perfect obedience to the Father's will.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The ephod made of gold, blue, purple, scarlet, and fine twisted linen — the realization of the instructions of ch.28. The five materials appear in order throughout the tabernacle: each is associated with graduated holiness (gold = divine; blue = heavenly; purple = royal; scarlet = sacrificial; fine linen = human purity). The incarnation integrates all five: in the one person of Christ, divine glory (gold) takes on heavenly (blue), royal (purple), sacrificial (scarlet), and perfectly human (linen) dimensions simultaneously.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The gold was hammered into flat sheets, cut into threads, and woven through the colored yarns. The gold threads running through the fabric — the divine substance interwoven with the human materials — is a remarkably precise type of the hypostatic union. The divine nature (gold) is not layered on top of but woven through the human materials (yarn). Christ is not God in a human costume but the eternal Son whose divine nature permeates his humanity as gold threads permeate the ephod.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The shoulder pieces made and joined at the ephod's upper edges. The joining of the shoulder pieces reflects the unity of the priestly office — two shoulders bearing a single garment. The double-shouldered ephod bearing the twelve names is the type of the two-natured Christ: fully human and fully divine, bearing the whole covenant people before God. The tension between the two shoulder pieces — separated yet united in one ephod — mirrors the theological tension that the Chalcedonian definition would later articulate.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The decorated waistband of the ephod was made the same way and of the same materials, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The waistband's unity with the ephod — one piece, not attached — represents the organic integrity of Christ's person and work. His priestly action (ephod) and his personal identity (waistband = core of the person) are not separable. Paul in Philippians 2:7 says he 'made himself nothing' — the kenosis is not a subtraction from his divine identity but its expression through the waistband-form of servant obedience.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Onyx stones mounted in gold filigree settings, engraved with the names of the twelve tribes. The precision: the names are engraved 'as one engraves a signet seal.' A signet seal impression cannot be altered — the identity it conveys is permanent and official. Christ's bearing of his people's names before God is similarly permanent and official: 'He has qualified you to share in the inheritance of his holy people in the kingdom of light' (Col 1:12). The filigree-mounted name-stone is the type of the permanent qualification that the cross achieves.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Fastened on the shoulder pieces of the ephod as memorial stones for the Israelites, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The repetition of 'just as the LORD had commanded Moses' (which occurs ten times in ch.39) is the execution-corresponds-to-instruction pattern. Hebrews 8:5 uses this exact pattern to argue for the tabernacle's typological function: Moses built it 'according to the pattern shown you on the mountain.' What Moses commanded is now executed; what the heavenly pattern showed is now built. Christ's priestly work is the final execution of the divine command.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The breastpiece made with the same skilled technique as the ephod, using the same materials. The breastpiece and the ephod are made of the same substance — the priest's decision-making organ (breastpiece of judgment) and the priest's working vestment (ephod) are of the same material and craftsmanship. Christ's intercessory work (breastpiece) and his priestly action (ephod) arise from the same person, the same nature, the same love. The high priest's heart-decision (breastpiece) and his service-action (ephod) cannot be separated.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The breastpiece folded double to make it square — equal on all sides. The perfect square of the breastpiece corresponds to the perfect cube of the most holy place (1 Kings 6:20) and the perfect cube of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:16). This geometric progression — square breastpiece → cubic holy of holies → cubic new Jerusalem — traces the movement of the divine presence from a portable ornament worn on the priest's chest, to a fixed sacred space, to the entire renewed cosmos filled with divine glory. The square breastpiece is the seed form of the new creation's shape.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The first row of stones: carnelian, topaz (chrysolite), and emerald. These begin the sequence that will appear as the foundations of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:19-20). The high priest's breastpiece is a portable new Jerusalem — the twelve-tribe community carried on the priest's chest into the divine presence. Jesus in Revelation is surrounded by the twenty-four elders (twelve patriarchs + twelve apostles — the double twelve) in the heavenly court, just as the twelve stones on the breastpiece surround the high priest as he enters the earthly most holy place.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The second row: turquoise, lapis lazuli, and moonstone. The lapis lazuli appears at the divine throne in Ezekiel 1:26 and at the covenant meal in Exodus 24:10. The breastpiece thus contains a fragment of the divine-throne stone — the priest carries the symbol of God's throne over his heart as he approaches God. Christ, whose right hand the Father has exalted to his own throne (Heb 1:3), carries his people's names over his heart as he sits at the divine throne — the living fulfillment of the lapis lazuli over Aaron's heart.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The third row: jacinth, agate, and amethyst. The deep purple and violet tones of this row reflect the royal register that runs through all the priestly vestments. The priest-king identity is woven into the very stones of the breastpiece. Psalm 110:1-4 holds together the two offices that the breastpiece embodies: 'Sit at my right hand' (royal enthronement) and 'You are a priest forever in the order of Melchizedek' (priestly consecration). The royal stones on the priestly garment are waiting for the one who holds both offices permanently.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The fourth row: beryl, onyx, and jasper — all set in gold filigree. The jasper, which ends the breastpiece's stone sequence, appears in Revelation as the first foundation of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:19) and as the appearance of the one on the throne (Rev 4:3). The stone sequence on the breastpiece thus begins and ends pointing to God: the priest who wears it is bracketed by the divine glory — everything he carries before God is encompassed within the divine presence that both sent him and receives him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'There was one stone for each of the twelve tribes of Israel, each engraved like a signet seal with the name of one tribe.' Each tribe is represented individually — no tribe merged with another, no name omitted. Jesus in John 17 intercedes for specific groups and individuals with the same particularity: 'I am not praying for the world, but for those you have given me' (17:9); 'I pray also for those who will believe in me through their message' (17:20). The individualized signet-seal names on the breastpiece are the type of the named intercession of the eternal high priest.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Braided chains of pure gold for the breastpiece. The chains ensure that the breastpiece — the heart-memorial of all twelve tribes — cannot fall away from the priest's chest. Hebrews 6:19-20: 'We have this hope as an anchor for the soul, firm and secure. It enters the inner sanctuary behind the curtain, where our forerunner, Jesus, has entered on our behalf.' The gold chains that secure the breastpiece to the ephod are the type of the hope that anchors the soul to Christ's presence in the divine inner sanctuary.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Gold settings and gold rings at the two upper corners of the breastpiece. The attachment of the breastpiece at its upper corners means that the names of the tribes are secured from the top — from above. Colossians 3:3: 'Your life is now hidden with Christ in God.' The security of the believer is from above — their life is secured in the heavenly realm, not dependent on earthly circumstances. The gold rings at the top corners of the breastpiece are the type of the heavenly securing of the covenant community.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The braided gold chains attached to the rings at the top of the breastpiece. The chain links are multiple and braided — strength through repetition and twisting. Paul's list in Romans 8:38-39 ('neither death nor life... nor anything else in all creation') is a braided chain: each link in the list adds strength to the whole. The braided-gold-chain security of the breastpiece is the type of the multi-strand, unbreakable security of the believer in Christ.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The other ends of the chains fastened to the gold settings on the ephod's front shoulder pieces. The breastpiece (heart) is thus connected to the shoulders (bearing work) at the top — the heart and the strength are linked. The great commandment (Matt 22:37-38) holds together these same dimensions: 'Love the LORD your God with all your heart (breastpiece) and with all your strength (shoulder).' The vestment structure anticipates the integration of love and power in the priestly vocation.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Two more gold rings at the lower inner corners of the breastpiece, next to the ephod. The structure is increasingly detailed — multiple rings, multiple attachment points, multiple chains. The redundancy of attachment points means no single point of failure can dislodge the breastpiece. John 10:28-30 has the same redundant security: 'No one can snatch them out of my hand... No one can snatch them out of my Father's hand. I and the Father are one.' Two hands, one grasp — the redundant attachment of the breastpiece is the type of the double security.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Two more gold rings on the ephod's lower front shoulder pieces, above the waistband. The multi-point attachment structure is now complete: breastpiece is secured at four corners to the ephod. The completeness of the attachment is as important as the strength of any single chain. Paul's 'nothing can separate us from the love of God' is similarly exhaustive (Rom 8:38-39): the comprehensive list ensures no loophole exists. The four-corner attachment of the breastpiece is the type of the all-encompassing security of those in Christ.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'They tied the breastpiece's rings to the ephod's rings with blue cord so that the breastpiece sat above the waistband and would not swing away from the ephod — just as the LORD commanded Moses.' The breastpiece must not swing loose. The object of this structural concern is theological: the names of the twelve tribes must always remain directly over the high priest's heart before God. The persistent, unwavering nature of Christ's intercession — 'He always lives to intercede for them' (Heb 7:25) — is the fulfillment of the structural concern that the breastpiece not swing away.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The robe of the ephod — woven entirely of blue. The all-blue robe under the colorful ephod is the foundation layer of the visible vestiture: before the priestly work (ephod) is visible, the heavenly identity (blue) must be put on. The order of vestition in 29:5 is tunic → robe → ephod → breastpiece, with the heavenly blue robe as the penultimate layer. For Christ, the foundation layer that underlies all his priestly work is his heavenly origin: 'I came from God and am here' (John 8:42); the eternal Son is the blue robe beneath the colorful vestments of incarnate ministry.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The robe's opening reinforced with a bound edge 'like a soldier's armor coat so it would not tear.' The seamless structural integrity of the high-priestly robe is completed in John 19:23-24: 'When the soldiers crucified Jesus, they took his clothes... This garment was seamless, woven in one piece from top to bottom. Let's not tear it, they said to one another. Let's decide by lot who will get it.' John records the seamless tunic as the fulfillment of Ps 22:18; the patristic tradition reads it as the high-priestly robe that must not be torn (Cyril, Origen). The un-torn vestment is the sign of the permanently valid priesthood.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Pomegranates of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn around the robe's hem. The pomegranate (<em>rimmon</em>) is the fruit whose many seeds enclosed in one skin symbolized the unity-in-multiplicity of the covenant people. The church is the pomegranate community: 'Because there is one loaf, we, who are many, are one body, for we all share the one loaf' (1 Cor 10:17). The many seeds enclosed in one skin correspond to the many members enclosed in one body of Christ — the fruit that hangs from the hem of the high-priestly robe as the sign of the community he represents.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Pure gold bells placed alternating with the pomegranates. The bells announce; the pomegranates symbolize. The priest's approach is both audible (bell = word) and visual (pomegranate = community). The new-covenant parallel is the church's twofold ministry: proclamation of the word (the bell, 1 Cor 1:17: 'I was sent to preach the gospel') and the gathering of the community (the pomegranate, John 11:52: 'to gather into one the scattered children of God'). The hem of the high priest's robe is a visual manifesto of the church's vocation.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Bell and pomegranate, bell and pomegranate, alternating all around the hem — for wear when ministering — just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The rhythmic alternation of sound and symbol mirrors the liturgical rhythm of Word and community: proclamation and gathering, speaking and embodying. The Sabbath rhythm — six days of labor, one day of rest — is encoded in creation; the bell-pomegranate rhythm of the priestly robe encodes the ministry rhythm: word-community, word-community, without interruption, all around the hem of the priestly garment.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Woven linen tunics for Aaron and his sons. The foundational garments — the tunics of fine linen worn next to the body — are the base of the entire vestiture. The linen against the skin represents the direct intersection of the sacred with the human. In baptism, the newly baptized was often given a white garment to symbolize the 'putting on of Christ' (Gal 3:27) — the linen tunic as the first and innermost layer of priestly dignity is the type of the new-covenant garment that every believer receives in baptism.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The turban, ornate headbands, and linen undergarments — the complete covering from head to waist. The turban (<em>mitznefet</em>) crowns the high priest; the headbands (<em>migba'ot</em>) crown the ordinary priests. Every priest is covered at the head, indicating that every member of the priestly community receives a form of the crown. In Revelation, the twenty-four elders have crowns (4:4); the victorious are crowned (2:10); the royal dignity of the priestly community reaches from the high priest's turban to the crowns of the redeemed community around the throne.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The sash of fine twisted linen embroidered with blue, purple, and scarlet — just as YHWH commanded Moses. The sash, like the waistband of the ephod, is the sign of girded readiness. Luke 12:35-37: 'Be dressed ready for service and keep your lamps burning, like servants waiting for their master to return... I tell you the truth, he will dress himself to serve, will have them recline at the table and will come and wait on them.' The priestly sash of readiness for service is fulfilled in Jesus who, at the Last Supper, wrapped a towel around his waist (John 13:4-5) to wash the disciples' feet — the high priest in the sash of a servant.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'They made the sacred plate (<em>tzitz</em>) of pure gold and engraved on it, as one engraves a seal: HOLINESS TO THE LORD (<em>qodesh laYHWH</em>).' The golden diadem's inscription is the summary of the entire tabernacle project: everything — the materials, the labor, the vestments, the furniture, the sacrifices — is consecrated to YHWH. Zechariah 14:20-21 describes the eschatological extension: 'On that day HOLY TO THE LORD will be inscribed on the bells of the horses... every cooking pot in Jerusalem and Judah will be holy to the LORD.' What is written on the high priest's forehead will one day be written on every common object in the new creation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A blue cord attaches the golden plate to the turban's front. The blue cord of the <em>tzitz</em> corresponds to the blue cord of the breastpiece (39:21) — the same heavenly blue thread that runs throughout the high-priestly vestiture. The blue cord is the sign of the heavenly connection: what the priest does on earth is directly connected to heaven. Jesus in John 3:13: 'No one has ever gone into heaven except the one who came from heaven — the Son of Man.' The blue cord of the holy plate is the type of the Son's essential heavenly connection that validates his earthly high-priestly ministry.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'So all the work on the tabernacle — the tent of meeting — was completed. The Israelites had done everything just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The completion formula echoes Genesis 2:1-2: 'Thus the heavens and the earth were completed in all their vast array... By the seventh day God had finished the work he had been doing.' The tabernacle's completion is a new-creation event. John 19:30: 'It is finished (<em>tetelestai</em>)' — Jesus's final word from the cross is the new-creation completion that the tabernacle's completion anticipated. The tabernacle's 'it was completed' is the OT foreshadowing of the cross's 'it is finished.'</p>",
    "33": "<p>They brought everything to Moses: the tabernacle and all its components. The covenant community brings the completed work before their mediator for inspection. The church presents itself before Christ at the judgment seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10; 1 Cor 3:13-15) — not for condemnation but for the assessment of its faithful stewardship. The bringing of the work to Moses anticipates the eschatological presentation of the community's work before the risen Lord, who as the new Moses inspects and accepts what was done in faithfulness.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The ram-skin covering dyed red and the leather outer cover; the inner curtain veil. The outer coverings of ram skins dyed red are the most visible element from outside the tabernacle. The red covering — suggesting the blood of the animal sacrifice — is what the watching world sees. The church presented to the world is similarly characterized by sacrifice: 'I carry on my body the marks of Jesus' (Gal 6:17); 'We are... regarded as sheep to be slaughtered' (Rom 8:36). The red covering that protects the tabernacle is the type of the sacrificial character that marks the visible community.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The ark of the testimony with its carrying poles and the mercy seat. The mercy seat (<em>kapporet</em>) — brought separately from the ark — is the lid that covers the testimony (the stone tablets of the law). The law is stored beneath the mercy seat: mercy covers the law, not eliminates it. Romans 3:25: God presented Christ as a <em>hilasterion</em> (mercy seat) 'to demonstrate his justice... so as to be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus.' The mercy seat placed on the ark of the law is the precise OT structure of the gospel: Christ placed over the law, not abolishing but covering it with atoning mercy.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The table with all its utensils and the bread of the Presence (<em>lechem ha-panim</em> — literally 'bread of the Face/Presence'). The showbread is the bread that is always before YHWH's face — twelve loaves representing the twelve tribes, replaced weekly, eaten by the priests. Jesus calls himself 'the bread of life' (John 6:35, 48) and 'the living bread that came down from heaven' (John 6:51) — the eternal bread of the Presence, always before the Father's face, always fresh, always available. The twelve loaves of the presence-bread are the type of the one eternal Bread who feeds the new twelve-tribe community.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The pure gold lampstand with its lamps arranged in order, utensils, and oil for the light. The menorah's lamps must be arranged in order and kept burning. John 8:12: 'I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will never walk in darkness, but will have the light of life.' Revelation 1:12-13 depicts the risen Christ walking among seven golden lampstands — he is both the light and the one who tends the lights, ensuring his churches give light in the world. The ordered, burning lamps of the golden lampstand are the type of the ordered, Spirit-filled community of witness that Christ tends.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The golden incense altar, the anointing oil, the aromatic incense, and the entrance screen. The incense altar burns continually before the veil — its smoke rising to YHWH as a fragrant intercession. Revelation 8:3-4: 'Another angel... was given much incense to offer, with the prayers of all God's people, on the golden altar in front of the throne. The smoke of the incense, together with the prayers of God's people, went up before God.' The golden incense altar is the type of the perpetual intercessory ministry of Christ through which the prayers of the saints rise before God.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The bronze altar with its grating, carrying poles, utensils, and the bronze basin with its stand. The bronze altar is the first encounter-point in the tabernacle complex — the place of sacrifice before approaching the holy place. 'No one comes to the Father except through me' (John 14:6): the bronze altar's mandatory-first-encounter structure is the type of Christ's cross as the unavoidable first step in approaching God. There is no path to the holy place (the Father's presence) that bypasses the bronze altar (the cross).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The curtains of the court, pillars and bases, the screen for the court gate, ropes and tent pegs. The outer court structure — the boundary of the sacred space accessible to Israel — forms the first level of graduated holiness. The church's gathering space is the new outer court: 'When you come together as a church' (1 Cor 11:18). The outer court where all Israel gathered anticipates the church where all nations may gather: 'a house of prayer for all nations' (Mark 11:17, citing Isa 56:7). The court that bounded Israel's access becomes the court open to the world in Christ.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The woven vestments for sanctuary service, the sacred garments for Aaron and his sons, all listed together. The complete catalog is presented before Moses. Hebrews 4:13: 'Nothing in all creation is hidden from God's sight. Everything is uncovered and laid bare before the eyes of him to whom we must give account.' The presentation of every completed item before Moses anticipates the final accounting when all things are laid before the one to whom we give account. The inventory is complete and nothing is missing — the type of the complete obedience that Christ fulfilled.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'The Israelites had done all the work exactly as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The exact obedience of the covenant community — not approximate but precise, not partial but total. Hebrews 5:8-9: 'Although he was a son, he learned obedience from what he suffered and, once made perfect, he became the source of eternal salvation for all who obey him.' Israel's exact obedience in building the tabernacle is the communal type of Christ's exact personal obedience — the one whose obedience was not just architectural but morally and spiritually perfect in every dimension.</p>",
    "43": "<p>'Moses inspected all the work and saw that they had done it just as the LORD commanded. And Moses blessed them.' The inspection, approval, and blessing by the mediator is the climactic verse of the construction narrative. Matthew 3:17 (and 17:5): 'This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased' — the Father inspects the work of the Son and blesses him. Moses's blessing of the obedient craftsmen is the OT type of the Father's 'well pleased' declaration over the obedient Son. Both blessings follow exact obedience; both authenticate the completed work for the service that follows.</p>"
  },
  "40": {
    "1": "<p>The LORD speaks to Moses — the divine commission begins the final chapter of Exodus, which moves from completion (ch.39) to consecration and indwelling (ch.40). The fact that YHWH must command the erection of the tabernacle — that it does not happen by human initiative — emphasizes that the divine dwelling with humanity is always God's initiative. John 3:16: 'God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son' — the move toward humanity is always from God's side. The tabernacle is not humanity's reaching toward God but God's reaching toward humanity, commanded and executed at divine initiative.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'On the first day of the first month, set up the tabernacle.' The new year, the first day — a new beginning. The command to erect the tabernacle on the first day of the new year echoes the first day of creation (Gen 1:3-5) and anticipates the 'first day of the week' of the resurrection (Matt 28:1). The tabernacle's establishment on the new year's first day is a re-creation event. The resurrection, which inaugurates the new creation, similarly happens on the first day — the new week, the new age, the new creation beginning.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Put the ark of the testimony inside and screen it with the inner veil.' The ark — the most sacred object — goes in first, behind the veil. The veil is the barrier that keeps the overwhelming divine presence from destroying the approaching worshipper. Matthew 27:51: 'At that moment the curtain of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom.' The veil erected in Exodus 40 is the veil torn at the crucifixion — the barrier that the cross removes. What Moses erects in obedience, Christ removes in sacrifice.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Bring in the table and arrange what belongs on it; bring in the lampstand and light its lamps.' The table (bread of the Presence) and the lampstand (light) are placed in the holy place. Jesus says in the same chapter in John where he claims to be the bread of life: 'I am the light of the world' (John 8:12, immediately after the bread-of-life discourse context of ch.6). The two furnishings of the holy place — table and lampstand, bread and light — are both fulfilled in the single person of Christ. The holy place anticipates the one in whom all its furnishings are embodied.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Set the golden incense altar before the ark of the testimony, and hang the entrance screen.' The incense altar stands between the holy place and the most holy place — between the area of priestly service and the divine presence. It is the locus of intercession, the fragrant smoke rising toward the divine. Hebrews 7:25: 'He always lives to intercede for them.' Christ as the living incense altar stands between the congregation (holy place) and the Father (most holy place), filling the space between with perpetual intercession.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Place the altar of burnt offering at the entrance to the tabernacle.' The bronze altar at the entrance — the first encounter, the unavoidable threshold of sacrifice — is the foundational structure of the covenant approach. Every worshipper who comes to YHWH comes first to the altar of burnt offering. There is no entrance into the tabernacle complex except through sacrifice. 'God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement' (Rom 3:25) — the bronze altar at the entrance is the type of the cross as the unavoidable first encounter with the living God. There is no path to the Father except through the Son's sacrifice (John 14:6).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Place the basin between the tent of meeting and the altar and fill it with water.' The bronze basin between the altar (sacrifice) and the tent entrance (approach) provides the washing that prepares the priests for holy-place service. The order — altar (atonement) → basin (washing) → tent entrance (approach) — maps onto the gospel order: the cross (atonement) → baptism (washing) → access to the Father (approach). Hebrews 10:22: 'let us draw near to God... having our hearts sprinkled to cleanse us from a guilty conscience and having our bodies washed with pure water.'</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Set up the surrounding court and hang the screen at the court gate.' The outer court — the boundary of sacred space — provides the first enclosure that separates the holy precincts from the surrounding world. The church is the new outer court: a visible, bounded community that marks the distinction between those gathered around the sacrifice and those outside. Hebrews 13:12-13 calls believers to 'go to him outside the camp' — the church's location is paradoxically outside (the old camp) and inside (the new court), gathered around the cross that redefines the sacred center.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Take the anointing oil and anoint the tabernacle and everything in it; consecrate it and all its furnishings, and it will be holy.' The anointing of the entire structure with oil — every piece of furniture, every curtain, every tent peg — consecrates the whole. The Spirit's anointing of the new-covenant community is similarly comprehensive: 'You have an anointing from the Holy One, and all of you know the truth' (1 John 2:20). The total anointing of the tabernacle is the type of the total anointing of the new-covenant community in Christ.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Anoint the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils and consecrate it, and it will be most holy.' The bronze altar — the place of sacrifice — is itself anointed and becomes 'most holy.' Whatever touches it becomes holy (29:37). The cross is the most holy object of the new covenant: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us' (Gal 3:13) — the cross, though bearing the curse and shame of crucifixion, is the most sacred place in history, the locus where divine love and divine justice meet in the person of the Son.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Anoint the basin and its stand and consecrate them.' The basin of washing is also consecrated with oil — the washing that cleanses the priests for service is itself anointed. Baptism as the new-covenant washing is administered in the name of the Trinity — it is a Spirit-anointed cleansing, not merely a water ritual. The oil-anointed basin is the type of the Spirit-accompanied baptism: 'one Lord, one faith, one baptism' (Eph 4:5), the single washing that constitutes membership in the new-covenant community.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance to the tent of meeting and wash them with water.' The washing at the threshold — before vestition, before anointing, before service. Hebrews 10:22: 'having our hearts sprinkled to cleanse us from a guilty conscience and having our bodies washed with pure water.' The order is consistent throughout: washing precedes approach. The cross provides the cleansing (blood); baptism enacts the cleansing (water); together they constitute the threshold-crossing that grants access to the divine presence.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Dress Aaron in the sacred garments, anoint him, and consecrate him so that he may serve me as priest.' The threefold act: vestition → anointing → consecration. The same three elements are present in Jesus's preparation for his ministry: baptism (washing/vestition of righteousness) → Spirit descent (anointing) → 'This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased' (consecration/blessing). Matthew 3:13-17 is the NT equivalent of Exodus 40:12-13 — the Son is prepared for his priestly ministry through the same three movements.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Bring his sons and clothe them with tunics.' The sons receive the priestly garments from the one who has already been anointed. Galatians 3:27: 'All of you who were baptized into Christ have clothed yourselves with Christ.' The church receives its priestly vestiture derivatively — from and through the already-anointed Son. The sons' tunics come from the father's ordination; the church's righteousness comes from the Son's righteousness. No believer earns or generates their own priestly clothing; it is received from the anointed one.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Anoint them as you anointed their father so they may serve me as priests. Their anointing will establish a lasting priesthood for all generations to come.' The derived anointing of the sons replicates the father's anointing. 1 John 2:20: 'You have an anointing from the Holy One' — the church's anointing is derived from Christ's anointing, replicating in the body what the head received. 2 Corinthians 1:21-22: 'God... anointed us, set his seal of ownership on us, and put his Spirit in our hearts as a deposit' — the Father anoints the church with the same Spirit with which he anointed the Son.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Moses did everything just as the LORD had commanded him.' The comprehensive obedience of Moses — a single sentence that summarizes his entire execution of the divine instructions. This single sentence is the human-obedience climax of the book's second half. Philippians 2:8: 'he humbled himself by becoming obedient to death — even death on a cross.' Christ's obedience exceeds even Moses's: Moses obeyed in building; Christ obeyed in dying. The comprehensive obedience of Moses ('everything') is the type of the comprehensive obedience of Christ ('to death').</p>",
    "17": "<p>'On the first day of the first month of the second year, the tabernacle was set up.' The precision of the redemptive calendar: a specific day, a specific month, a specific year. Galatians 4:4: 'when the fullness of time had come, God sent his Son.' The tabernacle erected on the specific first day of the first month of the second year is the OT pattern of the incarnation that occurred 'at the right time' (Rom 5:6). Divine redemption happens in history, at specific moments — not in timeless myth but in dateable events.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Moses set up the tabernacle: bases, frames, crossbars, pillars — the structural elements assembled in order. Paul's description of the church's construction is similarly ordered: 'built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, with Christ Jesus himself as the chief cornerstone. In him the whole building is joined together and rises to become a holy temple in the Lord' (Eph 2:20-21). The careful, ordered assembly of the tabernacle structure — each element in its proper place — is the type of the Spirit-ordered construction of the new-covenant temple.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'He spread the tent covering over the tabernacle and laid the outer cover on top — just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The covering goes over the structure — the inner beauty is hidden from the outside world. Isaiah 53:2: 'He had no beauty or majesty to attract us to him.' The tabernacle's beautiful interior (gold, fine linen, gemstones) is covered by the humble outer coverings of dyed leather. Christ's divine glory is similarly covered by the humble outer covering of human flesh — 'he made himself nothing, taking the very nature of a servant' (Phil 2:7), though within is the fullness of the Godhead.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Moses placed the testimony tablets in the ark, inserted the carrying poles, and set the mercy seat on top. The sequence is theological: law first, then mercy seat on top. The tablets of the law go inside the ark; the mercy seat — the <em>kapporet</em>, the atoning cover — is placed over them. Paul's logic in Romans 3:25-26 follows this structure: Christ as the <em>hilasterion</em> (mercy seat) is placed by God 'to demonstrate his justice... so as to be just and the one who justifies.' Mercy sits on top of justice; the mercy seat covers the law — not canceling it but fulfilling and covering it through Christ's atonement.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'He brought the ark into the tabernacle and hung the inner veil, screening off the ark of the testimony — just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' Moses hangs the veil that will separate the ark (divine presence) from the holy place (priestly service). The veil that Moses erects in obedience is the veil that the cross tears in fulfillment. Matthew 27:51: 'At that moment the curtain of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom.' The top-down tearing of the veil — not from human hands below but from divine hands above — signals that God himself has removed the barrier that he himself established.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Moses set the table on the north side outside the inner veil. The table with its bread of the Presence stands perpetually before the Lord, representing the covenant community in the divine presence. The Lord's Supper is the new-covenant table: 'This is my body, given for you' (Luke 22:19) — the bread on the table is no longer the twelve loaves representing the twelve tribes but the one bread of the one body of Christ. The community no longer brings bread to represent themselves; they receive bread that represents Christ, given for them.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'He arranged the bread on the table before the LORD, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The bread of the Presence arranged in order — twelve loaves in two rows (Lev 24:5-6). The orderly presentation of the covenant people before the LORD. In Revelation 7:4-8 the new-covenant community is also presented in ordered array: 144,000 from the twelve tribes (symbolic completeness). The ordered bread of the Presence is the type of the complete, ordered new-covenant community presented before God.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Moses placed the lampstand in the holy place, opposite the table, on the south side. The lampstand on the south faces the table on the north — light illuminates the bread. John 6:35: 'I am the bread of life'; John 8:12: 'I am the light of the world.' The pairing of bread and light in the holy place mirrors the pairing of incarnation and revelation: Christ feeds and illuminates. The lampstand that lights the table is the type of the light that illuminates the feast of the new covenant — the Spirit who sheds abroad the knowledge of Christ (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'He lit the lamps before the LORD, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The lampstand is lit — the light burns continually in the holy place. The lampstand that burns before the LORD is the type of the church's witness in the world: 'You are the light of the world... let your light shine before others' (Matt 5:14-16). But the ultimate fulfillment is Christ himself: 'The city does not need the sun or the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and the Lamb is its lamp' (Rev 21:23). The lamped holy place is the seed of the new Jerusalem that needs no sun.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Moses placed the golden incense altar in the holy place in front of the inner veil. The incense altar's position — between the congregation's approach and the divine inner presence, directly before the veil — is the position of the intercessor: between the people and God. Hebrews 9:24: 'Christ did not enter a sanctuary made with human hands... he entered heaven itself, now to appear for us in God's presence.' Christ in the heavenly holy place, before the Father, is the living incense altar — his presence before the Father is itself the intercession.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'And burned aromatic incense on it, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The incense burns — the fragrant prayer ascends. Revelation 5:8: 'the golden bowls full of incense, which are the prayers of God's people.' The golden incense altar where Moses burns aromatic incense is the type of the heavenly altar where the prayers of the saints ascend, mixed with the incense of Christ's own intercession (Rev 8:3-4). The earthly incense altar that Moses lights is the gateway to the heavenly altar that the risen Christ tends.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Moses hung the screen at the tabernacle's entrance. The entrance screen (not the inner veil, which screens the most holy place, but the outer screen) is the boundary between the holy place and the outer world. The church's gathering space is bounded by this outer screen — the threshold between the community of worship and the surrounding world. Matthew 18:20: 'where two or three gather in my name, there am I with them' — the gathered community with Christ present is the new outer screen, marking the space of his presence.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Moses placed the altar of burnt offering at the tabernacle's entrance and offered the first burnt offering and grain offering. The first sacrifice consecrates the altar and begins the covenant worship. Jesus's first public act at the Jordan — receiving baptism and the Spirit — similarly consecrates the beginning of his priestly ministry. But the 'first offering' of Christ's ministry that the bronze altar anticipates is the cross: 'he offered himself unblemished to God' (Heb 9:14) — the one sacrifice that all the daily burnt offerings pointed toward.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Moses placed the basin between the tent of meeting and the altar and filled it with water for washing. The basin of washing — between the sacrifice (altar) and the approach (tent entrance) — is the purification step between atonement and access. The gospel's order is preserved: the cross (altar, atonement) → baptism (basin, washing) → the church's gathered life (tent of meeting, access). None of the three steps can be bypassed; each flows from and leads to the next in the divinely ordered sequence of approach to God.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Moses, Aaron, and Aaron's sons washed their hands and feet at the basin. The hands and feet — the instruments of action and movement — are specifically washed. John 13:10: after Jesus washes the disciples' feet, he says, 'A person who has had a bath needs only to wash their feet; their whole body is clean.' The basin's hand-and-foot washing is the ongoing purification of one who has already been bathed in the initial washing (baptism): the daily walking in the world requires the ongoing foot-washing of repentance and forgiveness (1 John 1:9).</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Whenever they entered the tent of meeting or approached the altar, they washed — just as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The washing is habitual — every entry, every approach. The regular, repeated washing is the OT form of the NT's ongoing cleansing: 'If we walk in the light, as he is in the light... the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin' (1 John 1:7). The ongoing purification as a habitual practice, not a one-time event, is the lifestyle of those who 'draw near to God' (Heb 7:25; 10:22) through Christ.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'He set up the surrounding court around the tabernacle and altar and hung the screen at the court gate. So Moses completed all the work.' The completion formula: Moses 'completed all the work.' Genesis 2:2: 'By the seventh day God had finished the work.' Moses completing the tabernacle work is the second creation-completion in Scripture. Jesus's 'It is finished' (John 19:30) is the third — and the final. The sequence is: creation completed (Gen 2:2) → tabernacle completed (Exod 40:33) → atonement completed (John 19:30) → new creation completed (Rev 21:6: 'It is done').</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Then the cloud covered the tent of meeting, and the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle.' The climax of Exodus — the divine glory filling the completed tabernacle. This is the purpose toward which every chapter of the book has moved: YHWH dwelling with his redeemed people in the completed structure. John 1:14: 'The Word became flesh and made his dwelling (<em>eskenosen</em> — pitched his tent/tabernacled) among us. We have seen his glory (<em>doxa</em>), the glory of the one and only Son.' The glory-cloud filling the tabernacle is the type; the incarnate Son is the antitype. In the Son, the divine glory takes up permanent, personal residence in the human.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Moses was unable to enter the tent of meeting, because the cloud had settled on it and the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle.' The unapproachable, overpowering divine glory — even Moses, who had spoken with YHWH face to face (Exod 33:11), cannot enter. Hebrews 10:19-22 announces the transformation: 'We have confidence to enter the most holy place by the blood of Jesus... let us draw near to God with a sincere heart and with the full assurance that faith brings.' What Moses could not enter, Christ has opened: the way into the presence of the unapproachable glory is now available to every believer through the blood of the Son.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Whenever the cloud lifted from above the tabernacle, the Israelites set out on the next stage of their journey.' The cloud as the guide of the covenant community's pilgrimage — the divine presence that directs movement. John 16:13: 'when he, the Spirit of truth, comes, he will guide you into all the truth.' The cloud-guide of the wilderness pilgrimage is the type of the Spirit-guide of the new-covenant community's pilgrimage. The community follows the divine presence: not self-directed but Spirit-led, not setting their own course but following where the cloud lifts.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'But if the cloud did not lift, they did not set out — not until the day it lifted.' The community's movement is entirely determined by the divine initiative. Acts 16:6-10: the Spirit twice prevents Paul and his companions from going in a particular direction, then opens the Macedonian way. The apostolic mission moves by the Spirit's lifting and settling — the same cloud-guidance that directed Israel in the wilderness directs the church in its mission. The community waits on divine direction rather than acting on human initiative.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'The cloud of the LORD rested on the tabernacle by day, and fire glowed in the cloud by night — visible to all the house of Israel throughout all their journeys.' The final verse of Exodus: the visible, continuous divine presence with the entire covenant community, day and night, throughout every stage of the journey. Revelation 21:3: 'God's dwelling place is now among the people, and he will dwell with them. They will be his people, and God himself will be with them and be their God.' The last verse of Exodus is the seed; the vision of Revelation 21-22 is the flower. The cloud-and-fire presence that accompanied Israel through the wilderness is the type of the final, permanent, unmediated divine dwelling with humanity that is the goal of all redemptive history. Emmanuel — God with us — is the beginning (Matt 1:23), the middle (John 1:14), and the end (Rev 21:3) of the gospel.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, EXODUS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus', c)
    print('Exodus 39-40 mkt-christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
